The paper deals with privacy and adversarial models, which are typically studied in the sub-category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also involves mathematical tools such as Stein method, which is commonly used in information theory (cs.IT). The paper proposes a practical approach to utilizing adversarial uncertainty, which involves exploring the synergy between differential privacy and adversarial uncertainty, which falls under the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also deals with data sets that are dependent, which is a topic studied in the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper involves exploring the practical applications of the proposed approach, which falls under the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
